description.value: Gold amuletic figure of Thoth holding wedjat-eye.    Gold amuletic figure of Thoth: the Ibis-headed Thoth is depicted in the round, wearing a long wig and short kilt with ornate belt. By artistic convention, as a male, he walks with left foot advanced. He holds out before him the 'wedjat' eye with its characteristic markings. The whole piece was presumably cast in a mould with all details, including those of minute signs on the 'wedjat', being incised subsequently. There is a loop behind the figure's shoulders for suspension.

description.value: String of beads: green glazed steatite, shell, bone, coral, nenta shell and shell hippopotamus amulet.    Amuletic string with pendant: from the disturbed burial of a child, composed of many disc beads of various sizes and short cylindrical beads of shell; the ribbed long cylinders are 'Dentalium' shell tubes. The other short cylindrical beads are of bone and green glazed steatite. The long cylindrical beads are of bone, the drop-shaped pendant of ivory, and the hippopotamus amulet of shell. The hippopotamus stands with its feet joined together as though tied; it is pierced from front to back between its forelegs and hind legs for stringing. A large 'Nerita' shell completes the string.

description.value: A string composed of a number of tiny 'Conus' shells, two 'Natica' shells, one 'Nerita' shell, two long pointed pendants of ivory and a crouching hawk amulet of ivory. The latter has incised lines, filled with a black material, cut across the shoulders, centre of the body and tail. The widest part of the bird's body is perforated.
